{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567817"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19450"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19450"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.19,0.04,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12177"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84739"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12177"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69028"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1138"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"3833"},{"type":"tags","id":"8294"},{"type":"tags","id":"9419"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34971"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84739"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a growing lesion on his right ear. He works as a farmer and has extensive sun exposure throughout his life. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is an irregular, firm, erythematous 2 cm lesion with central ulceration and scaling on the right helix (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Keratoacanthoma","Malignant melanoma","Dermatofibroma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of a cutaneous malignancy on a sun-exposed area. \u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a firm, scaly or crusted lesion that may ulcerate. The irregular borders, scaling, and ulceration in an elderly patient with significant sun exposure history strongly suggest this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically has a pearly, rolled border with telangiectasia and a more regular appearance. While also common on sun-exposed areas, it tends to have a slower growth rate and is less likely to ulcerate early in its course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeratoacanthoma\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically presents as a rapidly growing dome-shaped nodule with a central keratin-filled crater. It typically develops over 4-8 weeks and may spontaneously resolve, which is not the pattern seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a pigmented lesion with irregular borders, varying colours, and asymmetry. The lack of pigmentation and the clinical appearance make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatofibroma\u003C/strong\u003E is typically a firm, brown-coloured nodule that occurs most commonly on the legs. It usually demonstrates the \u0027dimple sign\u0027 when compressed laterally and would be unusual in this location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe location on a sun-exposed area, the patient\u0027s age and occupation, and the clinical appearance with scaling and ulceration make squamous cell carcinoma the most likely diagnosis. Biopsy would be required for definitive diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma typically presents as a firm, scaly or crusted lesion that may ulcerate, commonly occurring on sun-exposed areas.","Key features distinguishing squamous cell carcinoma from basal cell carcinoma include more irregular borders, scaling, and tendency to ulcerate earlier.","Biopsy is essential to definitively distinguish between different types of skin cancer."],"references":["Rourke L, Oberholtzer S, Chatterley T, Brassard A. Learning to detect, categorize, and identify skin lesions: a meta-analysis. JAMA Dermatol. 2015;151(3):293-301. doi:10.1001/jamadermatol.2014.3300Clarke P.","Benign pigmented skin lesions. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019;48(6):364-367. doi:10.31128/AJGP-12-18-4802"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69028"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19450"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21530"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21530"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MQq0y2X4YbTKm0DVwQmrONyhQz5jhH.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MQq0y2X4YbTKm0DVwQmrONyhQz5jhH.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":360,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69028"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-10T15:44:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-10T15:45:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12177"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84739"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","